    <item>
      <title>Pedantry</title>
      <link>https://y6nh.github.io/pedantry/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 20 Apr 2017 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://y6nh.github.io/pedantry/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Naming things is difficult. We know that. But if you get it wrong, it can taint your whole product - at least, for pedants like me.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Today, I was investigating JavaScript Rest API testing frameworks. There seem to be two big names: &lt;a href=&#34;http://dareid.github.io/chakram/&#34;&gt;Chakram&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&#34;http://frisbyjs.com/&#34;&gt;Frisby&lt;/a&gt;, or its newer fork &lt;a href=&#34;https://github.com/MarkHerhold/IcedFrisby/&#34;&gt;IcedFrisby&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Chakram has a less silly name. It has a nice logo. Its documentation looks slicker. It appears more mature (IcedFrisby 1.0 is just 5 days old, as I write, and 1.1 is out already). The two frameworks seem to have much the same features, and I can live with the syntax either way.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-javascript&#34; data-lang=&#34;javascript&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;nx&#34;&gt;expect&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;p&#34;&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;nx&#34;&gt;response&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;p&#34;&gt;).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;nx&#34;&gt;to&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;p&#34;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;nx&#34;&gt;have&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;p&#34;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;nx&#34;&gt;status&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;p&#34;&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;mi&#34;&gt;200&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;p&#34;&gt;);&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

Nice.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-javascript&#34; data-lang=&#34;javascript&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;nx&#34;&gt;expect&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;p&#34;&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;nx&#34;&gt;response&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;p&#34;&gt;).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;nx&#34;&gt;not&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;p&#34;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;nx&#34;&gt;to&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;p&#34;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;nx&#34;&gt;be&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;p&#34;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;nx&#34;&gt;encoded&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;p&#34;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;kd&#34;&gt;with&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;p&#34;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;nx&#34;&gt;gzip&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;p&#34;&gt;;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

Cute.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-javascript&#34; data-lang=&#34;javascript&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;nx&#34;&gt;expect&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;p&#34;&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;nx&#34;&gt;response&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;p&#34;&gt;).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;nx&#34;&gt;to&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;p&#34;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;nx&#34;&gt;comprise&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;p&#34;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;k&#34;&gt;of&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;p&#34;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;nx&#34;&gt;json&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;p&#34;&gt;({&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

NO. I AM NOT TYPING THAT.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s the sort of thing we get &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User:Giraffedata/comprised_of&#34;&gt;obsessive&lt;/a&gt; about.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I know, this stuff &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/feb/05/why-wikipedias-grammar-vigilante-is-wrong&#34;&gt;isn&amp;rsquo;t important&lt;/a&gt;. It&amp;rsquo;s not really English anyway, it&amp;rsquo;s machine instructions, and the parser doesn&amp;rsquo;t care, and for someone who doesn&amp;rsquo;t speak English the whole of JavaScript is just arbitrary symbols&amp;hellip;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And I&amp;rsquo;m pretty sure the &lt;code&gt;.of&lt;/code&gt; &lt;a href=&#34;http://chaijs.com/api/bdd/#language-chains&#34;&gt;does absolutely nothing&lt;/a&gt;, and could be left out, or replaced with any number of filler words, like &amp;ldquo;.to.be.is.to.have.and.to.have.is.to.be&amp;rdquo;&amp;hellip;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;But I choose IcedFrisby.&lt;/p&gt;
